        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer377263651" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16867793744187523387">Despite the fact that the book is so depressing (for all the injustice mentioned in the book), it takes the reader deeply in the world of the book. It touches your heart.<br/><br/>The prisoners were unbelievably idealistic to me (compared to the characters in Sharaf by the author Sonalla Ibrahim). They were very righteous, logical, and selfless; characteristics that would disappear in such an ordeal. For the prison keepers, I still don&apos;t get how they turn into such sadistic creatures! The author did expla</span>
  <span id="freeText16867793744187523387" style="display:none">Despite the fact that the book is so depressing (for all the injustice mentioned in the book), it takes the reader deeply in the world of the book. It touches your heart.<br /><br />The prisoners were unbelievably idealistic to me (compared to the characters in Sharaf by the author Sonalla Ibrahim). They were very righteous, logical, and selfless; characteristics that would disappear in such an ordeal. For the prison keepers, I still don't get how they turn into such sadistic creatures! The author did explain the turn briefly but still... <br /><br />I liked the fact that the author did not specify a country (even though it was obvious what country it was, from the dialogue); the torturing for political cases happens in every Arab country. <br /><br />The thing about reading prison literature is that one sees and appreciates the little things in his life; the little things that are the basic of freedom. <br /><br />ربنا يفك أسر كل المحبوسين ظلما </span>
  <a data-text-id="16867793744187523387" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


