<div id="review_2450967173" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2450967173" />
    <a title="Yaman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/68316449-yaman"><img alt="Yaman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614423897p2/68316449.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2450967173?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Yaman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Yaman" href="/user/show/68316449-yaman">Yaman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2450967173" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1597069528472754150"><br/>Writing this review in English as I hope that sharing it might make you want to pick up the translated version – audiences in the non-Arab World are unfamiliar with the dense issue that is being discussed here. I’d say not even most Arabs are aware of its extent. <br/><br/>It has been a very long while since I found a book compelling enough for me to read it in one sitting. &quot;The Shell: Memoirs of a Hidden Observer&quot; is... unbelievable, to say the least. It’s definitely one of the most, if not the most, pow</span>
  <span id="freeText1597069528472754150" style="display:none"><br />Writing this review in English as I hope that sharing it might make you want to pick up the translated version – audiences in the non-Arab World are unfamiliar with the dense issue that is being discussed here. I’d say not even most Arabs are aware of its extent. <br /><br />It has been a very long while since I found a book compelling enough for me to read it in one sitting. "The Shell: Memoirs of a Hidden Observer" is... unbelievable, to say the least. It’s definitely one of the most, if not the most, powerful and courageous works I’ve ever put my hands on. <br /><br />A Catholic man from Syria returns home after studying in France, only to be picked up at the airport by Syrian intelligence. He’s then sent to spend the next decade of his life in a military prison – Palmyra Military Prison, as implied by context. All part of the insanity that drove Assad (the father) to turn the entire country into one large prison in the 1980s.<br /><br />Prisons under both Assads, in general, have long been considered hell on earth, matched in barbarity by none other than North Korea. They’ve been documented as inhumane slaughterhouses by human rights agencies, and while reading this book I could only remember Amnesty International’s detailed report and pictures exposing one of these torture chambers. <br /><br />This book is talking exactly about that. It’s a shocking account on the ugly, revolting nature of these prisons. I can’t find the proper words to describe the level of dehumanization imposed on prisoners of conscience in Syria, but this book does. Its pages show the reader the sickening sadism committed on arbitrary basis in these prisons to subjugate Syrians and humiliate them into becoming slaves to the regime and its militias. <br /><br />Reading this book might make you feel nauseous, but that’s exactly the point: it’s an honest description of life in Assad’s Syria. Definitely a must-read for anyone interested in Syria’s past and why it lead to Syria of the present. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1597069528472754150" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


