<div id="review_2255456025" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2255456025" />
    <a title="Peter King" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14042714-peter-king"><img alt="Peter King" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442649435p2/14042714.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2255456025?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Peter King" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Peter King" href="/user/show/14042714-peter-king">Peter King</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/34329421-the-shell">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2255456025" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16681868347297684111">This book doesn&apos;t read like a normal novel - more like an autobiography. It&apos;s the story of a Syrian who finds himself imprisoned by the Assad regime for being Muslim Brotherhood, although he&apos;s actually a Christian and the Syrian authorities neither know nor care why he&apos;s in prison. <br/>Frankly, it&apos;s a tough read. I thought reading about Treblinka was tough. This was on a par. It&apos;s awful. It&apos;s basically a story of mental survival. Living, crammed closely with people who mistrust, despise and hate you</span>
  <span id="freeText16681868347297684111" style="display:none">This book doesn't read like a normal novel - more like an autobiography. It's the story of a Syrian who finds himself imprisoned by the Assad regime for being Muslim Brotherhood, although he's actually a Christian and the Syrian authorities neither know nor care why he's in prison. <br />Frankly, it's a tough read. I thought reading about Treblinka was tough. This was on a par. It's awful. It's basically a story of mental survival. Living, crammed closely with people who mistrust, despise and hate you while your guards casually torture you (500 lashes on the feet is the standard punishment for opening your eyes in the exercise yard) and execute people randomly around you. <br />Mustafa Khalifa's depiction is not drawn entirely from his own 12 year stint in Tadmur prison but is an amalgam of experiences of others. It is about the damage done to human beings by terror and personality cults and makes clear that Assad is fundamentally no different to Saddam Hussein or any other post-war Middle East CIA creation.This is not a Disney story. There is no happy ending, there is only a kind of numb relief. <br />If you feel slightly sorry for yourself, this book is the antidote. If you are interested in Syria and the Middle East, this book is essential to understand the evil of the Assad regime. But fun or enjoyable, it is not.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16681868347297684111" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

