<div id="review_1575405377" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1575405377" />
    <a title="Moez Lamti" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13583336-moez-lamti"><img alt="Moez Lamti" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1558849018p2/13583336.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1575405377?book_show_action=true">Sep 23, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Moez Lamti" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Moez Lamti" href="/user/show/13583336-moez-lamti">Moez Lamti</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1575405377" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2676122600083161664">Notwithstanding the terror of real events which the story is a pale representation of, this book is quite weak. And except for some occasional lyrical escapades here and there, the best being centred around the symbolism of the titular shell itself, everything else is a lifeless description of the mundane life of a Christian captive in Syrian prisons sometime in the early eighties. There is bitter irony and a lot of insignificance in the situation, but the writer lacked the skill to turn it into</span>
  <span id="freeText2676122600083161664" style="display:none">Notwithstanding the terror of real events which the story is a pale representation of, this book is quite weak. And except for some occasional lyrical escapades here and there, the best being centred around the symbolism of the titular shell itself, everything else is a lifeless description of the mundane life of a Christian captive in Syrian prisons sometime in the early eighties. There is bitter irony and a lot of insignificance in the situation, but the writer lacked the skill to turn it into art. . It's clear the writer has given up any effort to find meaning around him, and why wouldn't he, given the absurdity of what befell him, but that's so damn depressing that any reader would like to see an inkling of light even if it flaunts the precepts of reality. An interesting part of the narrative relates to Muslim brothers, who were portrayed with candid admiration; they seemed to possess what he lacked: calm and matter-of-fact reaction to imminent death. Yet for obvious ideological reasons, the writer could never part of that group, or part of any other community either. It's a story of a kafkaesque entity with blunted instincts and no hope of redemption who wonders why doesn't he die.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2676122600083161664" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

